For example, he reasons in favour of religious liberty, from the difficulty of expound- ing the Scriptures so as to arrive at any certain conclu- sion on some points, from the incompetency of PopeS, Councils, or the church at large, to determine articles of saith, from the innocence of error, where there is real piety 3 and from the antiquity and plausibility of various sentiments and practices generally held to be erroneous. It is more on such grounds as these that he rests his de- fence of toleration, than on the inherent and essential rights of men, and the authority of the word of God. Such an advocate can scarcely be recognized as pleading for the same principles with Williams, Owen, and his other clerical contemporaries in the same nomina] field.
